{"_id":"586a87b0-bc7a-11ea-b1e0-c91656e94b0d","postId":"2013_11_taskrun-etiquette-examples-even-in-92009538-82a4-3754-9963-fbe116fda88e","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2013/11/taskrun-etiquette-examples-even-in.html","replyTo":"e03edb40-bc76-11ea-b1e0-c91656e94b0d","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"I generally prefer to use `Task.Run` to run work on a background thread. The drawback to the `await something().ConfigureAwait(false)` approach is that the asynchronous work *must* run asynchronously; if `something()` completes before the `await` is evaluated, then the code continues executing without switching to a background thread. If you use `Task.Run`, then the code passed to `Task.Run` *always* runs on a background thread.","date":"2020-07-02T15:40:24.571Z"}